<HEAD>Plans For Nuclear Ghost Town Released</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disposal of eight old, closed reactors
that produced plutonium fuel for the nation's nuclear weapons could
cost $217 million and take more than 100 years, according to a
draft plan released Thursday.
   The pioneering reactors, some of which date back to the
Manhattan Project during World War II, are on the Hanford federal
nuclear reservation in south-central Washington and have been idled
for years.
   ``No future long-term use of any of the eight surplus production
reactors has been identified by the DOE,'' said the draft
environmental impact statement by the Department of Energy.
   They are the nation's first defense production reactors proposed
for permanent disposal, said Roger Freeberg, chief of Hanford
restoration for the DOE.
   Although the reactors' nuclear fuel has long been removed, they
are still contaminated with 98,100 curies of tritium, 37,400 curies
of carbon-14, 74,400 curies of cobalt-60 and other radioactive
materials that could threaten workers and the environment, the plan
said. A curie is a measure of radioactivity.
   That is why they must be decommissioned or placed in a condition
that ensures public safety and protects the environment, DOE said.
   Five disposal alternatives _ from burying the reactors to
leaving them intact _ were discussed in the report.
   The Energy Department will choose one of the five alternatives
by late 1990, Freeberg said. None of the disposal methods pose any
radiation threat to the public, the report said.
   The eight hulking reactors, built between 1943 and 1955, stand a
few miles apart along the Columbia River. They employed thousands
of workers making highly radioactive plutonium for the nation's
nuclear weapons.
   But from 1964 to 1971 they were shut down one by one as the need
for plutonium, which lasts thousands of years, diminished.
   Only one operable defense reactor, the N Reactor, remains at
Hanford and it is closed because of a plutonium surplus. The
nation's only other defense reactors are at the Savannah River
Plant in South Carolina.
   Among reactors slated for decommissioning is the B Reactor, the
world's first full-size nuclear reactor. It was built during a
crash 15-month period in 1943-1944 as the nation raced to develop
an atomic bomb before Nazi Germany. In fact, the Nazis were far
from developing nuclear weapons.
   The reactor sites should not be abandoned because maintenance is
needed to prevent the release of the remaining radioactivity, the
report said.
   Alternatives studied were:
   _Continue the present routine monitoring and maintenance. Over
100 years, this would cost $41 million in 1986 dollars, with
minimal radiation doses to workers.
   However, at the end of 100 years the reactors and some
radioactive contamination would remain, requiring additional work,
the report said.
   _Immediately move the 9,000 to 11,000-ton reactor vessels to a
Hanford burial site several miles away. This would take about 12
years for all eight reactors, cost about $191 million and be more
hazardous for workers.
   _Wait 75 years for radiation levels to subside before moving the
reactor vessels to the burial site. That would allow radioactive
cobalt 60, a significant threat to workers, to decay and reduce
worker exposure to radiation by an estimated two-thirds.
   This plan would cost $198 million and take 87 years before all
12 reactors would be buried.
   _Wait 75 years and then dismantle each reactor so the waste
could more easily be transported for burial. This plan is most
expensive at $217 million, and would take 103 years for all eight
reactors.
   Worker exposure is over 10 times greater than any other
alternative because workers would be inside the reactor vessel, the
report said.
   _Bury the 46-feet-tall reactor vessels under 16 feet of soil at
their present sites, after the surrounding buildings have been
removed.
   This plan would take five to six years to complete, at a total
cost of $181 million. Except for the proposal to maintain present
conditions, this is the safest alternative for workers.
</TEXT>
