   Officials spent Saturday laboriously trying to
track down truck drivers, warehouse workers and others who may have
been exposed to an intensely radioactive pellet buried within a
transcontinental cargo shipment.
   The radioactive pellet _ the size of a pencil eraser _ was
discovered Thursday lying loose in a shipment of what were supposed
to have been empty containers trucked to Massachusetts. The pellet,
called a source, is used for making X-ray-type pictures of welds,
structural steel and other industrial objects.
   Technicians at the shipment's last stop, Amersham Inc. of
Burlington, discovered the pellet when they detected radioactivity
coming from the shipment of containers used to carry sources. The
container that the source was found in lacked a shielding device
that would have prevented the radiation from leaking out.
   ``It's safe to say that this is extraordinarily rare,'' said
Karl Abraham, a Nuclear Regulatory Commission spokesman. ``There
should be concern but certainly not panic until we have a chance to
contact all the individuals who have had exposure.''
   Abraham said it would take several days to determine how many
people may have received radiation during the shipment's transit
from South Korea to Los Angeles, where it was stored for a month
before being trucked cross-country to Amersham, which manufactures
equipment used to test industrial structures.
   ``It appears to be an old source, a decayed source,'' Abraham
said of the pellet. New pellets radiate at a level of 60 to 75
curies; radiation from the one that was found was at levels from 3
to 7 curies, he said.
   Initial measurements taken 4 to 6 inches away form the pellet
found the level of radiation to be 150 rems per hour _ millions of
times higher than that people normally are exposed to from the
environment and X-rays. A rem is a measure of the estimated damage
done to living tissue by radiation.
   People generally receive about one-tenth of a rem, or 100
millirem, of radiation annually from natural sources; the average
American is exposed to an annual dose of 77 millirem from medical
X-rays.
   Abraham said investigators would better be able to determine the
radiation field after reconstructing the way in which the cargo was
stored.
   ``Then we have to determine the relation of that to where the
driver was sitting, where the people in the warehouse were and how
long these people were near the source,'' he said. ``It's going to
be a laborious process that will take many days.''
   The NRC has enlisted the help of state officials in
Massachusetts, California, Pennsylvania and Maryland in their
efforts to reconstruct the radioactive shipment's path. The Sate
Department has also contacted the South Korean government, he said.
   Abraham said it wasn't immediately clear how or at what point
the radioactive pellet slipped into the cargo, but ``the shipment
supposedly came in sealed up under bond like most things do when
they go from one continent to another.''
