<HEAD>Report: High Radiation Levels Detected In Soviet Arms Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Karachay Lake, a 100-acre body of water in the
Soviet Union, could be ``the most polluted spot on the planet,''
the result of years of radioactive waste dumping, according to a
published report today.
   U.S. experts who recently visited a Soviet nuclear weapons
production complex found extremely high levels of radioactive
contamination and a history of high doses to production workers,
The New York Times reported.
   The Soviets have confirmed that in 1951, atomic bomb makers
began pumping radioactive wastes into Karachay Lake _ about 900
miles east of Moscow _ a practice that continued until the
accumulation reached 120 million curies.
   That amount is about 2{ times greater than the release from the
Chernobyl nuclear accident in 1986.
   ``This has got to be the must polluted spot on the planet,''
said Thomas B. Cochran, a physicist and senior staff scientist at
the Natural Resources Defense Council, a private environmental
group in Washington.
   The dose rate on the lake shore near the outlet pipe is 600
roentgen per hour, according to a new report by Cochran and Robert
Standish Norris, also at the council.
   At that rate, one hour's exposure would kill a person within
weeks, the Times reported.
   The Times said Soviet documents describe a ``sanitary alienation
zone'' in contaminated areas in which people are forbidden to live
or travel. The zone's size was unknown.
   ``Provided you keep away from it, which they are, it is causing
no harm to public health,'' said Richard Wilson, a Harvard
University physicist who has studied the Soviet nuclear complex.
``I would characterize it as greater than anything we've even
contemplated in this country.''
   Recent Soviet disclosures also show very high worker exposures,
the newspaper said.
   Other scientists who have visited the area recently say the lake
was extremely contaminated, but they disagreed on the degree of
contamination.
   Estimates ranged from as high as 600 roentgen per hour down to
six, said Frank L. Parker, an engineering professor at Vanderbilt
University and chairman of the National Academy of Sciences board
on radioactive waste management. He was at the Chelyabinsk site in
June.
   But whether 600 or six, Parker said, both constitute an
``astronomical dosage.''
   Even the lower figure would surpass the maximum allowable
exposure for an American worker for a year, the Times reported.
