<LEADPARA>  PARTICIPANTS FROM the United States, the Soviet Union and Britain met recnetly
at the National War College for an annual discussion of security concerns.;   
Most of the topics were the expected fare: military reform in the Soviet
Union, security implications of the struggle between the union and the
republics and strategies for converting the defense establishment to the
civilian economy. Sandwiched among these was one surprise -- a session devoted
to "The Environmental Dimension of Security." The subject was introduced a
trifle apologetically by the American chairman, who feared his colleagues
might find the subject "soft."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  UNION OF SOVIET SOCIALIST POLLUTION  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Jessica Mathews, vice president of World Resources Institute, wrote this
article for the Washington Post.
Commentary  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The Americans did seem to find the topic far removed from their concerns.
They had little to contribute.;    The Russians, on the other hand, leaped to
the discussion with enthusiasm. Though they have more immediate worries --
their country's survival and the role of its military being more than a little
uncertain -- they have no difficulty accepting direct linkage of the words
"environment" and "security.";    Environmental trends;  For more than 40
years, national security for our two countries was defined strictly in terms
of the other's military capability and intentions. The term has since
broadened. Reflecting the importance of economic strength, the United States
created the post of undersecretary of state for economic affairs and a
comparable office on the National Security Council staff in the 1970s.;   
Much more recently, the contribution of environmental trends has begun to be
discussed outside -- but not inside -- the national security establishment. In
this respect, thinking (though not management) in the Soviet Union has
progressed further than it has here.;    One reason is that environmental
conditions in the Soviet Union's one-sixth of the planet are so appalling that
no one needs to explain the nature of the threats or the national interests
that are at stake. Some of them were described at the War College by Boris
Porfiriev of the Soviet Academy of Sciences.;    Nuclear contamination figures
prominently, beginning with the still mysterious accident at Kyshtym. Unknown
in the West for 20 years, the explosion's cause and consequences are still
unclear, though large amounts of radioactivity were released, thousands
evacuated and land permanently removed from production.;    Much worse was the
chronic dumping of radioactive waste in nearby Chelyabinsk at the site of the
USSR's first plutonium production facility. Over the years, vast amounts of
radioactivity -- more than 1 billion curies -- were released directly into
surrounding rivers and lakes. These connect with the Ob River basin, whose
waters may be spreading an environmental disaster over a much larger
territory.;    Chernobyl;  And then, of course, there is Chernobyl.;    Even
for this Gorbachev-era, non-military accident, the facts are elusive.
Porfiriev puts the number of those living in contaminated areas at 4 million,
much more than previous surveys. Five years later, the toll in polluted land,
cancers and radiation disease is still rising. Evacuations of more than
100,000 additional people are expected, and more than half a million people
are under permanent medical observation.;    Major Gen. I. Danilenko described
visiting the village where he grew up, which lies just outside the
30-kilometer evacuated radius around the plant. Villagers receive what the
bureaucrats call an "economic incentive" to stay there. They call it
"graveyard money.";    Even so, radioactivity is probably the least of the
Soviet Union's environmental woes. Industrial pollution is endemic. The
distinguished biologist A.V. Yablokov classifies 15 to 20 regions, in which
more than half of the USSR's population lives, as environmental crisis areas.;
   "Every third man in those regions has a cancer . . . and the average life
expectancy is four to eight years shorter than in the developed countries.";  
 Soil destruction;  Worst of all in long-term economic costs may be the
mismanagement and destruction of agricultural soils. The country's richest
prairie-like soils have lost half of their natural productivity. Erosion is
rampant.;    Major fisheries have been destroyed. Pesticide poisoning is
widespread. The list goes on and on, and all of today's sketchy statistics are
probably underestimates.;    That said, Porfiriev calculates that the cost of
pollution and natural resource degradation, including health costs but not
victim compensation, amounts to 15 to 17 percent of GNP.;    This is roughly
equal to, or perhaps greater than, the Soviet Union's disputed defense budget.
(The United States spends 12 percent of its GNP on health and 13 percent on
energy.) While I found Porfiriev's estimate to be staggering, none of the
Russians seemed surprised by it. Those I asked guessed it was too low.;   
Russians also have had more direct exposure than we to the transnational and
global environmental ills that cross militarily defended borders with
impunity. Because of how the winds blow, the Soviet Union is on the receiving
end of more air pollution than it exports. As any Canadian will tell you, in
the United States it is the reverse.;    Redefining U.S. national security
without the Soviet threat as its organizing principle is proving to be
difficult.;    We have no consensus yet on what our essential interests are,
and threats without enemies behind them don't seem very threatening. As the
national debate proceeds, we may find that we have something to learn from the
Russians, though it comes at a tragic cost to them and possibly to the world.  </TEXT>
