<HEAD>Contents Of Storage Tanks At Nuclear Reservation Sometimes A
Mystery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There is a potentially explosive witches'
brew cooking inside 177 nuclear waste storage tanks at the Hanford
nuclear reservation.
   Surrounded by steel and concrete, buried under several feet of
earth, and roasting at temperatures of 140 degrees, the radioactive
slurry changes in ways that scientists cannot always predict.
   Scientists working for the U.S. Department of Energy concluded
that hydrogen gas trapped beneath the hard crust of the waste in 20
of the tanks could explode, releasing up to 3 million curies of
radiation from a single tank.
   The wastes are generated by nuclear weapons production.
   Hanford was created as part of the Manhattan Project to beat
Nazi Germany to the atomic bomb during World War II. The Department
of Energy, in a cost-cutting move, recently announced it is
shutting down the only federal reactor still operating in the
south-central Washington town.
   ``We've got good data on what went into those tanks,'' Don
Wodrich, a scientist with contractor Westinghouse Hanford Co., said
last week. ``But over the years, it blended together and mixed. Now
it's more complicated.''
   The insides of the tanks are far too lethal for human entry. All
scientists can do is monitor the temperature and vapors escaping
through filtered vents, and occasionally send a probe into the guck.
   But probes of the 20 suspect tanks have been stopped, because
scientists fear a spark could trigger an explosion.
   The explosion potential was announced March 23, along with a
unique admission that DOE really isn't sure how dangerous the
situation is. The agency said it will take until June to come up
with a solution plan.
   That has prompted criticism from Congress and a citizens'
watchdog group, who contend the department knew about the danger
years ago.
   The Energy Department have stated repeatedly that the explosion
risk is low, although they will not have a safety analysis
completed for two weeks.
   Spokesman Ken Morgan has said there is more danger to the public
from a gasoline truck than from the tanks, and called the
controversy the ``cold fusion'' of disasters, referring to the
highly disputed claim that the nuclear process known as fusion can
be created in an ordinary laboratory.
   That attitude infuriates Hanford critics.
   ``They don't fully accept their responsibility to protect public
health and safety,'' said Jim Thomas of the Hanford Education
Action League in Spokane. ``They should have been doing risk
analysis on this stuff years ago.''
   Energy Department officials insisted last week they became aware
of the explosion potential only in February, even though they
detected hydrogen in the wastes as early as 1983.
   Hanford Manager Mike Lawrence, in announcing the problem, said
he had become aware of the danger only the day before. If that is
the case, said Thomas, then Hanford apparently has major management
problems.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said a study prepared for the Energy
Department in June 1985 warned of potential problems with gases in
some Hanford tanks. That report examined only the liquid and solid
waste in the tanks, but said the gases should be addressed in
another study.
   Wyden said the 1985 report ``seems to contradict this whole
notion that the Energy Department didn't know anything about it.''
   The 1985 hydrogen study was a companion to another study on
whether ferrocyanide in some tanks could explode. The ferrocyanide
report was leaked to reporters last October.
   Under criticism for its handling of that issue, the Energy
Department decided to take a broader look at the explosion
potential in all Hanford tanks, and scientists discovered the
hydrogen problem in late February, scientist Wodrich said.
   The explosion threat is apparently not similar to the presumed
cause of a nuclear waste storage tank explosion in the Soviet Union
in 1957 that may have killed hundreds.
   Al Conklin of the state Office of Radiation Protection said the
Soviet explosion involved a different mixture of chemicals and a
lengthy breakdown of the tank's cooling system.
   The DOE is most concerned about one tank, called 101-SY, that
contains 1 million gallons of mixed radioactive waste. Some wastes
dumped into the tank in the 1970s contained organics, which are now
decomposing and giving off hydrogen gas. The organics were used to
separate radioactive strontium from other wastes before they were
stored.
   The most dangerous gases are those trapped in air pockets under
the hard crust. Scientists are unsure how much gas is beneath the
waste, although they credit the gas with raising the waste level by
up to 33 inches.
   Wodrich said DOE officials are confident the explosion risk is
low because the hydrogen gas has apparently existed in the waste
for years, and that new precautions are being taken to prevent an
explosion.
   In a briefing for state regulators, Wodrich said tank 101-SY was
completed in 1976 and is 75 feet in diameter and 35 feet tall. The
double-walled tank contains about 32 feet of waste.
   The tank also contains 8,000 gallons of water inserted in
1984-1988, when DOE made an unsuccessful attempt to reduce the gas
buildup by breaking through the crust. The crust develops from the
drying of the wastes.
