<HEAD>Hospital Believes Crate with Radiation Sent to Netherlands</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: new material throughout with crate thought to have been sent
back to Netherlands.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at Georgetown University Hospital
believe missing radioactive material taken from the hospital was
sent back to the Netherlands, a spokeswoman said today.
   The hospital had been trying to locate a crate containing a
potentially fatal dose of radioactive iridium it believed was
accidentally taken from the hospital.
   But hospital spokeswoman Carol Fox said today that officials
found some documents on Wednesday that indicated the missing
radioactive material was picked up by the manufacturer on April 20.
   She said the paperwork indicated that the iridium had been sent
back to the Netherlands where it was supposed to have been returned.
   The hospital will be in contact with the manufacturer and hopes
to be able to confirm later today that the shipment is safe and on
track, King said.
   The radioactive iridium was protected by a blue, steel-jacketed
lead shield and is braced to keep it in the center of the crate.
   ``Assuming the source is still contained in the lead shield and
still packaged inside the crate, radiation exposure rates should be
minimal,'' said a hospital statement released Wednesday. ``If,
however, the source has been removed from the shielding, it
presents a potentially serious, possibly fatal, risk to anyone who
may handle it.''.
   The hospital said earlier the iridium was believed taken by a
courier on April 20 and a Georgetown radiation control officer
discovered what was believed to be a mistake 10 days later.
   The hospital notified the Nuclear Regulatory Commission that a
search for the crate failed.
   The square 18-inch crate bears a shipping label to Georgetown
University Hospital.
   The label on the crate also reads, ``Caution: Radioactive.
Handle Carefully, Iridium 192, 10 Curies, Transportation Index:
.6.''
